sbol:Collection.dcterms:title: iGEM Parts Registry
sbol:Collection.dcterms:description: The iGEM Registry is a growing collection of genetic parts that can be mixed and matched to build synthetic biology devices and systems. As part of the synthetic biology community's efforts to make biology easier to engineer, it provides a source of genetic parts to iGEM teams and academic labs.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_I8021
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:description: Booperator test: RhlR biasing, RhlR/LuxR crosstalk
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: This is the second test chassis for the Booperator and it tests for crosstalk across the HSL signals and biasing of the RhlR receiver and inverter.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Srini Devadas, David Gray, Ronny Krashinsky, Debra Lin, and Chris Zheng Liu

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: RhlR+C4
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
Promoter activated by RhlR in concert with C4-HSL. C4-HSL is produced by RhlI, and acts as a quorum-sensing autoinducer.

This is the natural sequence taken from Pseudomonas aeruginosa.

Crosstalk: this promoter is also activated at a low level by LasR with its associated HSL.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Ronny Krashinsky
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
The -10 and -35 sites are labeled as identified in [Pearson97].

The part begins with the RhlR binding site, and (rather arbitrarily) ends with the first transcribed base (+1).

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: cI HK022
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Coding region for the HK022 bacteriophage cI protein. cI binds to the HK022 pR regulator (BBa_R0050). It represses transcription of the protein encoded by the sequence 3' to the pR region. This coding sequence does not contain a RBS.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Reshma Shetty
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
References (unparsed) here:

Carlson NG, Little JW. Highly cooperative DNA binding by the coliphage HK022 repressor. J Mol Biol. 1993 Apr 20;230(4):1108-30.
PMID: 8487297.

Mao C, Little JW. Mutations affecting cooperative DNA binding of phage HK022 CI repressor.
J Mol Biol. 1998 May 29;279(1):31-48. PMID: 9636698.

References (unparsed) here:

PMID: 8487297.

Mao C, Little JW. Mutations affecting cooperative DNA binding of phage HK022 CI repressor.
J Mol Biol. 1998 May 29;279(1):31-48. PMID: 9636698.

Derived from STHK022N.

Response from John Little (Arizona) regarding the start of HK022 cI

From:
Date: Tue Jan 21, 2003 4:39:21 PM US/Eastern
To: "Drew Endy"
Subject: RE: hk022 cI start (naive question)?
Hello Drew and Michael, I seriously doubt that the extra 27 aa are part of CI. It doesn't make sense in terms of the biology, for sure. In any case, the protein we characterized starts where Carlson and Little stated; as I recall, oR3 partially overlaps the start of cI. I have a vague memory of some possibly interesting biology, having to do with multicopy plasmids. I don't recall the findings themselves. Anyway, one possible explanation was that this extra N-terminal addition was made (e.g. from the pRE promoter, or from a message that arose from transcription around the entire plasmid), making a protein with altered functions. We never followed it up.
Good luck
John

-- Original Message --
Date: Sun, 19 Jan 2003 15:26:26 -0500
Subject: hk022 cI start (naive question)?
Cc: elowitm@rockefeller.edu
To: jlittle@u.arizona.edu
From: Drew Endy
Hi John, I'm sitting here with Michael Elowitz and we're working through the sequence for HK022 cI. We noticed that the annotation from NC_002166 includes an "extra" 81 base pairs upstream of what we thought of as the actual start. It looks like this extra DNA extends into the PR regulatory region. We're wondering what's going on here? I'm guessing this is well documented somewhere. Thanks for any pointers/info!
Drew

It is unknown whether there is cross-talk between this repressor and Lambda cI regulatory region, 434 cI regulatory region and P22 regulatory region.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: BBa_B0012
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: Transcription terminator for the E.coli RNA polymerase.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Reshma Shetty
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableProvenance: Derived from the TE terminator of T7 bacteriophage between Genes 1.3 and 1.4 <genbank>V01146</genbank>.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Suggested by Sri Kosuri and Drew Endy as a high efficiency terminator. The 5' end cutoff was placed immediately after the TAA stop codon and the 3' end cutoff was placed just prior to the RBS of Gene 1.4 (before AAGGAG).

Use anywhere transcription should be stopped when the gene of interest is upstream of this terminator.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: cI HK022
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription: The pR regulatory region is a 98 base-pair sequence with standard BioBrick prefix and suffix sections on its ends. It contains two operator sites at which HK022 cI protein can bind cooperatively. The -35 and -10 regions from pR are included along with some flanking sequences. The cutoff for the 5' end of the regulatory region was placed just after the pM -10 region which promotes transcription of a gene upstream (thus the pM -10 region is not included). The cutoff for the 3' end of the regulatory region was placed immediately prior to the RBS.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Reshma Shetty
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes:
Derived from STHK022N.

Literature claims that there is no cross-talk between HK022 cI regulatory region, Lambda cI, 434 cI and P22 cI, but this has not been verified experimentally by the synthetic biology group at MIT.

sbol:ComponentDefinition.dcterms:title: luxr
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableDescription:
In complex with HSL, LuxR binds to the Lux promoter, activating transcription from Pr BBa_R0062, and repressing transcription from Pl BBa_R0063.

The lux cassette of V. fischeri contains a left and a right promoter. The right promoter gives weak constitutive expression of downstream genes.This expression is up-regulated by the action of the Lux activator, LuxR complexed to HSL. Two molecules of LuxR protein form a complex with two molecules the signalling compound homoserine lactone (HSL). This complex binds to a palindromic site on the promoter, increasing the rate of transcription.
sbol:ComponentDefinition.dc:creator: Vinay S Mahajan, Voichita D. Marinescu, Brian Chow, Alexander D Wissner-Gross and Peter Carr
sbol:ComponentDefinition.sbh:mutableNotes: 2 silent point mutants were introduced in the coding sequence to remove internal XbaI and PstI sites. Mutation sites were chosen to replace codons commonly used in E. coli with codons used at a similar frequency.
